{
  "texts": [
    "DistilBERT (Sanh et al. 2019), in an opposite direction than RoBERTa, simplifies the initial architecture of BERT, by reducing the number of layers in the BERT-base model by a factor of 2, removing token embeddings and poolers in order to yield a much smaller and faster version of BERT for general-purpose use.",
    "DistilBERT is capable of language modelling and can be pre-trained on other language modelling tasks.",
    "It is faster and lighter than original BERT, but still suffers from context fragmentation (Acheampong et al. 2021).",
    "XLNet (Yang et al. 2019) is an auto-regressive language model that utilizes the concepts of the Permutation Language Model (PLM) and the Transformer-XL model to achieve the SOTA.",
    "As a BERT variant, the significant difference between the BERT and the XLNet has to do with their training objective."
  ]
}